+# Sinex documentation map
+
+Sinex is a local evidence substrate for digital life and agent work. It preserves acquired material, records versioned interpretations, exposes gaps and readiness explicitly, and derives cross-source products without turning model output into authority.
+
+This page is the shortest route through a large repository. Roadmap authority lives in Beads. Deep technical documents describe the implementation; they do not override the owning Bead when future work changes.
+
+## In 30 seconds
+
+Read:
+
+1. [Product and purpose](product.md) — what Sinex is, what it refuses to conflate, and why agents need it.
+2. [Public demonstrations](demos.md) — what can be reproduced now and what the stronger proof portfolio is designed to establish.
+3. [Proof and claims](proof-artifacts.md) — the difference between deterministic proof, private-deployment observation, experiment, and roadmap direction.
+
+The category sentence is:
+
+> **Sinex is a local, replayable evidence substrate for a person's and machine's digital activity.**
+
+The compact mental model is:
+
+```text
+source material
+    → versioned interpretations
+        → typed events and domain objects
+            → rebuildable projections
+                → evidence-backed products and context
+```
+
+## In three minutes
+
+Read these sections:
+
+- [The five evidence layers](product.md#the-five-evidence-layers)
+- [Three clocks](product.md#three-clocks-not-one)
+- [Replay](product.md#replay-means-reinterpretation-not-erasure)
+- [Missing evidence](product.md#missing-evidence-is-a-result)
+- [Confidence and authority](product.md#confidence-is-not-authority)
+- [Polylogue on Sinex](polylogue-integration.md)
+- [Sinex-Polylogue machine contracts](interop/README.md)
+
+Then run the existing deterministic operational walkthrough:
+
+```bash
+xtask infra start
+xtask run core --logs
+sinexctl ops verify --demo
+```
+
+The walkthrough is a bounded smoke proof of real API/query paths. It is not yet the full proof of Sinex's product thesis. That distinction is deliberate.
+
+## In thirty minutes
+
+Read in this order:
+
+1. [Architecture deep dive](architecture.md) — provenance, identity, replay, storage, runtime, and privacy.
+2. [Knowledge boundaries](../crate/sinex-primitives/docs/knowledge_boundaries.md) — source material, interpretations, typed records, graph products, and workspace artifacts.
+3. [Evidence lanes](../crate/sinexd/docs/sources/evidence_lanes.md) — acquisition payloads, replayable snapshots, and storage roles.
+4. [Event taxonomy](../crate/sinex-db/docs/schema/event-taxonomy.md) — canonical event storage.
+5. [Domain reducers](../crate/sinex-primitives/docs/domain_reducers.md) — how current state is reconstructed from event history.
+6. [Runtime quality of service](../crate/sinexd/docs/runtime_qos.md) — backpressure, boundedness, and failure policy.
+7. [Read-only MCP](../crate/sinexctl/docs/mcp_readonly_server.md) — the current agent evidence boundary.
+8. [Polylogue integration](polylogue-integration.md) — the maximal transcript-backend target and its impedance mismatches.
+
+## By task
+
+| I need to… | Start here |
+|---|---|
+| Explain Sinex to a new reader | [Product and purpose](product.md) |
+| Reproduce the current demo | [Generated demo walkthrough](../crate/sinexctl/docs/demo_walkthrough.md) |
+| Understand what public claims are supportable | [Proof and claims](proof-artifacts.md) and [`public-claims.yaml`](public-claims.yaml) |
+| Design a source | [Source package template](../crate/sinexd/docs/sources/source_capture_package_template.md) |
+| Understand source gaps | [Evidence lanes](../crate/sinexd/docs/sources/evidence_lanes.md) and [runtime QoS](../crate/sinexd/docs/runtime_qos.md) |
+| Understand replay and identity | [Architecture](architecture.md#identity-occurrence-vs-interpretation) |
+| Build a projection | [Domain reducers](../crate/sinex-primitives/docs/domain_reducers.md) and [derivation catalog](../crate/sinexd/docs/automata/derivation_catalog.md) |
+| Query or operate Sinex | [sinexctl docs](../crate/sinexctl/docs/README.md) |
+| Give an agent evidence access | [MCP contract](../crate/sinexctl/docs/mcp_readonly_server.md) and [agent orientation](../crate/sinexctl/docs/agent_orientation.md) |
+| Deploy or harden it | [NixOS guide](../nixos/README.md) and [API transport security](../crate/sinexd/docs/api/transport_security.md) |
+| Understand Polylogue as a Sinex-backed product | [Polylogue integration](polylogue-integration.md) |
+| Work on the roadmap | `bd ready`, then inspect the owning Bead |
+
+## Authority and status labels
+
+Public-facing prose should use these labels consistently:
+
+- **Implemented** — present in the supplied code and reachable through a named surface.
+- **Deterministically proven** — reproducible from a checked-in fixture or demo packet with a structural oracle.
+- **Observed in deployment** — measured on a named private deployment; not a general benchmark.
+- **Experimental** — evaluated under a declared protocol, with limitations.
+- **Planned** — owned by a Bead and not described as shipped.
+- **Retired** — historical design or issue references that no longer own work.
+
+A result also needs an evidence class: structural, source-material, independently recomputed, human-adjudicated, heuristic, or unavailable. Status and evidence class answer different questions.
+
+## Roadmap authority
+
+GitHub Issues are retired as the planning surface. Use Beads:
+
+```bash
+bd ready
+bd list --status open
+bd show <id>
+```
+
+When a design document and its owning Bead disagree about future work, the Bead wins. Current code and schemas remain authoritative for what is actually implemented.
