@@ -0,0 +1,277 @@
+# Polylogue on Sinex
+
+Status: target architecture and execution contract. The current implementation is a metadata-thin bridge; the full backend is planned under Bead `sinex-4j2` and corresponding Polylogue work.
+
+The companion [machine-readable authority, identity, and transcript-revision contracts](interop/README.md) make the target falsifiable before runtime implementation.
+
+## Executive decision
+
+In a Sinex-backed deployment, Sinex should ultimately store:
+
+- provider-native transcript artifacts;
+- original attachment bytes;
+- immutable normalized Polylogue transcript material;
+- durable session, message, tool, topology, usage, assertion, judgment, and context-delivery history;
+- lifecycle, deletion, model-effect, and cross-domain relation records;
+- rebuildable server-side Polylogue projections.
+
+Polylogue should remain responsible for:
+
+- provider and origin normalization semantics;
+- the session/message/block/tool ontology;
+- fork, continuation, subagent, shared-prefix, and compaction semantics;
+- physical-versus-logical composition and accounting;
+- AI-work query behavior;
+- reviewed memory and context compilation;
+- transcript, forensic, coordination, and handoff UX.
+
+Polylogue SQLite remains:
+
+- the standalone authority when Sinex is not configured;
+- a local/offline projection, cache, and outbox in Sinex-backed mode;
+- a deterministic development and demo backend;
+- a home for genuinely local presentation state.
+
+The division is:
+
+> **Sinex owns durable persistence and evidentiary lifecycle. Polylogue owns AI-work semantics and product behavior.**
+
+## Why the metadata-only bridge is insufficient
+
+The current source contract publishes a session-indexed summary with IDs, origin, title, tags, hashes, timestamps, counts, model, and optional cost. That is useful for low-volume correlation, notifications, and migration.
+
+It cannot establish that Sinex is Polylogue's backend because it cannot:
+
+- rebuild transcript content;
+- resolve messages and tool evidence;
+- preserve attachments;
+- reconstruct session lineage;
+- restore assertions and judgments;
+- reproduce context delivery;
+- apply lifecycle and deletion coherently;
+- reuse model effects over the same content;
+- audit parser reinterpretation.
+
+The low-volume event remains useful as a notification and health lane. It should not define the ultimate storage boundary.
+
+## Five layers
+
+```text
+1. Provider-native material
+   exports · JSONL · browser payloads · hook streams · attachments
+
+2. Polylogue-normalized material
+   sessions · messages · blocks · tool calls/results · usage lanes
+
+3. Sinex evidence and lifecycle
+   material refs · versioned interpretations · judgments · effects · deletion
+
+4. Derived and cross-domain products
+   logical sessions · work episodes · Agent Work Packets · findings · context candidates
+
+5. Polylogue product surfaces
+   transcript views · search · audit · memory · coordination · handoff
+```
+
+Layer boundaries prevent two failure modes:
+
+- reducing Polylogue to generic event JSON and destroying its domain semantics;
+- leaving all meaningful transcript evidence in isolated SQLite while Sinex receives only summaries.
+
+## Authority matrix
+
+| Data class | Sinex-backed authority | Polylogue SQLite role |
+|---|---|---|
+| Provider-native artifacts | Sinex material plane | Spool/download cache |
+| Attachments | Sinex material plane | Local cache |
+| Normalized transcript segments | Sinex material plane | Projection source/cache |
+| Durable session/message/block history | Sinex domain history under Polylogue semantics | Rebuildable index |
+| Current transcript view | Rebuildable PostgreSQL projection | Rebuildable edge projection |
+| Logical session topology | Polylogue-defined, durably recorded in Sinex | Local composed-read index |
+| Usage and cost observations | Sinex durable history | Local analytic cache |
+| Candidate assertions | Sinex proposal history | Offline replica/outbox |
+| Judgments and accepted memory | Sinex durable authority | Local replica |
+| Context image bytes | Sinex artifact/material | Local cache |
+| Context delivery occurrence | Sinex durable event | Local audit projection |
+| FTS and vectors | Rebuildable projection | Local acceleration |
+| UI layout, scroll, temporary filters | Local SQLite | Local authority |
+| Pending offline writes | Local outbox until admitted | Temporary local authority |
+| Beads task state | Beads | Reference/cache only |
+
+No irreplaceable durable AI-work state should silently exist only in SQLite in backed mode.
+
+## Identity model
+
+Four identities must remain separate:
+
+| Identity | Meaning |
+|---|---|
+| Stable Polylogue object ID | Logical session, message, block, assertion, or context delivery |
+| Polylogue revision ID | One content or semantic revision of that object |
+| Sinex event ID | One admitted interpretation in a replay epoch |
+| Material occurrence ref | Exact provider-native or normalized record/byte anchor |
+
+Sinex event UUIDs change on replay. Public Polylogue refs must not.
+
+A durable identity/alias registry is therefore required. Content digests and material offsets help reconciliation but are not sufficient object identity.
+
+## Transcript ingestion protocol
+
+### 1. Stage source material
+
+Polylogue stages provider-native bytes and receives Sinex material IDs. Material records carry source, origin, digests, size, media/record format, acquisition interval, privacy class, completeness, and replayability.
+
+### 2. Seal normalized segments
+
+Polylogue writes immutable bounded normalized segments. A revision manifest names:
+
+- raw material refs;
+- normalized segment refs;
+- parser semantics version;
+- expected sessions/messages/blocks/tools/attachments;
+- aggregate digests;
+- privacy and coverage metadata.
+
+Immutable segments are safer than anchors into a regenerated mutable JSONL file.
+
+### 3. Emit compact observations
+
+The admitted event vocabulary includes session lifecycle, messages, tool calls/results, subagents, compaction, attachments, usage, assertions, judgments, and context delivery.
+
+Large text and bytes stay in material. Events carry typed metadata, stable object and revision IDs, sequence, source-domain time, semantics version, material anchor, and privacy class.
+
+### 4. Settle the revision bundle
+
+A transcript revision needs expected counts, digests, child settlement, retry state, and a committed frontier. Readers see either the prior complete revision or the new complete revision, not an apparently complete half-import.
+
+### 5. Build Polylogue projections
+
+Polylogue-owned reducers/projection workers reconstruct current sessions, message order, blocks, tool pairing, topology, usage, assertions, and context delivery in PostgreSQL and SQLite.
+
+### 6. Prove rebuild
+
+The decisive command is conceptually:
+
+```bash
+polylogue rebuild --from-sinex
+```
+
+The proof drops rebuildable SQLite state, reconstructs it from Sinex material and domain history, and explains every difference. Local UI state and explicitly unsupported legacy material are excluded by contract.
+
+## Impedance mismatches and resolutions
+
+### Replay identity versus stable public refs
+
+Sinex interpretations receive new UUIDs on replay. Polylogue refs need stable object IDs and revision aliases.
+
+### Mutable sessions versus immutable evidence
+
+A session grows and can be resumed or re-exported. Model it as stable identity plus immutable revision manifests and segments, not `(session_id, content_hash)` as one occurrence key.
+
+### Material anchors can move
+
+Byte and line offsets are exact only inside immutable material. Seal segments and retain record IDs so public refs survive reserialization.
+
+### Sinex derivation provenance is not Polylogue lineage
+
+Fork, continuation, shared prefix, subagent, and compaction are domain relationships. They must not be encoded as Sinex derivation parentage or deletion cascades will be wrong.
+
+### Physical evidence versus logical work
+
+Sinex preserves every physical artifact. Polylogue composes copied prefixes, unique tails, logical sessions, and physical/logical token views. Generic event counts must never be presented as unique work counts.
+
+### Event volume
+
+Messages and tool calls are first-class. Not every UI implementation row needs a canonical event. Subordinate block details can remain in normalized material/projections unless they have independent lifecycle or forensic significance.
+
+### Transaction-like completeness
+
+Use revision manifests and settlement so an asynchronous pipeline cannot expose a partial session as complete.
+
+### Ordering
+
+Preserve source time, but add session sequence, provider ordinal, block ordinal, tool correlation, causal predecessor, and revision ordering. Never sort a transcript by `ts_coided`.
+
+### Query shape
+
+Sinex's generic event query is not a substitute for Polylogue's transcript, lineage, action-sequence, cost, assertion, and context queries. Polylogue remains the domain query service over Sinex-backed projections.
+
+### User-authored durable state
+
+Marks, corrections, notes, lessons, handoffs, judgments, and context policy must be reconstructable from Sinex in backed mode. Merely mirroring “an annotation happened” is insufficient.
+
+### Context packs
+
+Sinex supplies broad evidence candidates and source gaps. Polylogue owns AI-work selection and trust policy. One final context artifact and one delivery event record exactly what crossed the model boundary.
+
+### Model effects
+
+Effect identity includes content digest, canonicalization, selector/chunking recipe, provider, model revision, dimensions, task/input type, and normalization. `(provider, model, content_hash)` alone can collide.
+
+### Content hashes
+
+Sinex and Polylogue currently use different digest conventions. Store a multi-digest content descriptor; do not turn either digest into domain identity.
+
+### Privacy and access
+
+Transcript storage, embedding, and agent disclosure are separate policies. Raw text need not travel in generic NATS payloads or generic MCP responses, but it can still be durably stored in Sinex's protected material plane.
+
+### Deletion
+
+Deletion must cover raw material, normalized segments, event interpretations, server projections, SQLite replicas, FTS, vectors, context artifacts, reports, and model-effect inputs. Polylogue topology relationships must remain distinct from derivation lineage during cascade.
+
+### Standalone and backed deployment
+
+Support two explicit profiles:
+
+- standalone Polylogue: SQLite is authoritative;
+- Sinex-backed Polylogue: Sinex is durable authority and SQLite is a local replica/outbox.
+
+Do not permit silent dual-master behavior.
+
+### Agent tool surface
+
+Sinex and Polylogue each expose many MCP tools. The combined product needs a small workflow-oriented front door—orient, search, resolve/show, compile context, inspect work packet, propose assertion, inspect readiness—while full low-level catalogs remain specialist surfaces.
+
+## Joint products enabled by the architecture
+
+### Evidence-backed resumption
+
+A new agent receives Bead intent, prior sessions, actual Git state, failed and successful commands, reviewed lessons, stale-memory warnings, and source gaps. The delivered context is itself recorded.
+
+### Claim versus machine effect
+
+The system compares assistant prose, provider tool outcomes, ambient terminal evidence, Git state, CI results, and operator judgment without collapsing them.
+
+### Compaction forensics
+
+Polylogue supplies context boundaries and summaries. Sinex supplies surrounding machine activity and source state. The combined view can investigate whether omitted context plausibly contributed to later failure.
+
+### Stale-memory detection
+
+A reviewed assertion tied to repository state can be marked for review when relevant files, commits, or tasks change.
+
+### Agent Work Packets
+
+A packet can relate Bead intent, sessions/subagents, repository/worktree, commands, changes, tests, CI, source materials, outcomes, and reviewed lessons. Every leg remains a native ref; missing legs remain explicit.
+
+## Delivery phases
+
+1. Supersede the metadata-only storage decision and publish the authority matrix.
+2. Establish stable object/revision/material identity.
+3. Stage provider-native and normalized material.
+4. Emit the full observation vocabulary.
+5. Add revision settlement and projection watermarks.
+6. Build PostgreSQL Polylogue projections and SQLite replication.
+7. Move durable user judgment and context-delivery history into Sinex.
+8. Share model-effect recipes and retrieval evaluation.
+9. Deliver reverse context, moments, and Agent Work Packets.
+10. Prove deletion, offline reconciliation, replay-stable refs, and full SQLite rebuild.
+
+## Public status wording
+
+Use:
+
+> Sinex currently receives a metadata-thin Polylogue signal. The planned `sinex-4j2` architecture makes Sinex the durable material and event backend while Polylogue remains the AI-work domain and product. The transition is complete only after full transcript storage, stable identity, revision settlement, and a from-Sinex rebuild proof land.
+
+Do not say “Polylogue runs on Sinex” until that proof exists.
