@@ -0,0 +1,197 @@
+# Sinex: product, purpose, and value
+
+## The one-sentence explanation
+
+**Sinex is a local, replayable evidence substrate for digital life and agent work.**
+
+It acquires heterogeneous material, records versioned interpretations of that material, preserves temporal and provenance distinctions, makes source gaps visible, and derives higher-order products without silently promoting inference into truth.
+
+## The problem
+
+Important work is scattered across systems that do not share an ontology or a reliable clock:
+
+- shell histories and process outcomes;
+- Git repositories, branches, commits, and worktrees;
+- browser visits and research;
+- desktop focus and application state;
+- files, exports, logs, and documents;
+- task and issue systems;
+- model calls, agent sessions, and context deliveries;
+- operator notes and judgments.
+
+Collecting rows is not enough. A useful evidence system has to distinguish:
+
+- nothing happened from capture failed;
+- occurrence time from import time;
+- acquired bytes from a parser's interpretation;
+- a new interpretation from a duplicate occurrence;
+- a model proposal from an accepted fact;
+- current state from the event history that produced it;
+- a convenient summary from the evidence it summarizes.
+
+Sinex is designed around those distinctions.
+
+## The five evidence layers
+
+| Layer | Examples | What may be claimed |
+|---|---|---|
+| **Source material** | Export files, local databases, immutable snapshots, transcript archives, attachment bytes | These bytes or records were acquired under this source contract |
+| **Material interpretations** | Parsed commands, visits, messages, file observations | This parser and semantics version interpreted this material this way |
+| **Domain objects and projections** | Current task state, current transcript view, attention stream | This is the current rebuildable domain view under declared reducer semantics |
+| **Derived graph and products** | Work episodes, relations, Agent Work Packets, findings | This computation related these evidence objects under this algorithm and scope |
+| **Workspace artifacts** | Context packs, reports, semantic diffs | This saved product was generated; it is not automatically canonical truth |
+
+The boundary is deliberately asymmetric. Evidence can produce a report. A report repeated by a model does not automatically become evidence.
+
+## Three clocks, not one
+
+One observation can have several relevant times:
+
+- `ts_orig`: when the occurrence happened in its source domain;
+- `ts_coided`: when Sinex minted this interpretation;
+- `ts_persisted`: when the interpretation became durable.
+
+A provider conversation may have occurred in January, been imported in July, and be reinterpreted after a parser fix in August. A single timestamp cannot represent all three facts honestly.
+
+Queries about when something happened use occurrence time. Queries about when Sinex learned or reinterpreted it use coining time. Persistence time describes pipeline delay and storage behavior.
+
+## Replay means reinterpretation, not erasure
+
+An event ID identifies one interpretation. It is not the permanent identity of the underlying real-world occurrence.
+
+When parser or derivation semantics change, Sinex can:
+
+1. preserve the source material;
+2. archive or supersede the prior interpretation according to lifecycle policy;
+3. emit a fresh semantics-versioned interpretation;
+4. rebuild affected projections;
+5. retain enough provenance to explain the change.
+
+This means the system can change its mind without pretending it never held the earlier interpretation.
+
+Occurrence identity, interpretation identity, and stable domain-object identity are separate concerns. This separation is particularly important for a Sinex-backed Polylogue, where public session and message references must survive replay even though Sinex event UUIDs do not.
+
+## Missing evidence is a result
+
+An empty result may mean:
+
+- no matching occurrence exists;
+- the source was disabled or stale;
+- source material exists but has not been interpreted;
+- a projection is behind;
+- a continuity gap exists;
+- the requested evidence is not replayable;
+- privacy policy suppresses the material;
+- the query is unsupported.
+
+Sinex's coverage and readiness work exists so those states can be represented instead of collapsed into an authoritative-looking empty list.
+
+This is central to the product. A system that cannot describe its blind spots is not an evidence system; it is a confident partial database.
+
+## Confidence is not authority
+
+Models and heuristics can propose:
+
+- entity merges;
+- project attribution;
+- work-episode labels;
+- relations;
+- lessons;
+- task candidates;
+- context candidates.
+
+A confidence score measures a model or heuristic's assessment. It does not grant write authority.
+
+The intended lifecycle is:
+
+```text
+evidence
+    → proposal
+        → operator judgment or declared policy
+            → promoted state
+```
+
+The proposal, its evidence, the judgment, and the promoted state remain separately inspectable. This prevents agents from recursively canonizing their own earlier guesses.
+
+## Why this matters for agents
+
+An agent transcript records a partial point of view. It may contain the prompt, a plan, tool calls, tool results, and final prose. It does not necessarily contain the wider machine state or the complete evidentiary outcome.
+
+Sinex can add:
+
+- terminal commands outside the provider transcript;
+- actual Git and filesystem changes;
+- browser research;
+- task intent;
+- source outages and capture gaps;
+- other agents' activity;
+- deployment or verification evidence;
+- model-effect and context-delivery records.
+
+Together with Polylogue, the system can distinguish:
+
+```text
+what the agent claimed
+what its tool result structurally reported
+what the machine independently observed
+what repository or deployment state changed
+what a human accepted as durable memory
+```
+
+That distinction is the basis for reliable resumption, context compilation, postmortems, and agent evaluation.
+
+## Architecture at a glance
+
+```text
+files · databases · streams · exports · external producers
+                              │
+                       source contracts
+                              │
+                material registry + content store
+                              │
+                 adapters + versioned parsers
+                              │
+                     NATS JetStream transport
+                              │
+          event engine: validate · time · privacy · persist
+                              │
+              PostgreSQL canonical evidence plane
+                              │
+              automata · reducers · projections · search
+                              │
+              API · sinexctl · MCP · context consumers
+```
+
+NATS is transport, not archive authority. Large or sensitive bytes belong in the material plane. Compact typed observations reference exact material and pass through the admitted event path.
+
+## What Sinex is not
+
+Sinex is not:
+
+- a generic event viewer whose ontology is arbitrary JSON;
+- an activity score or behavioral-nudging product;
+- a vector database with provenance added later;
+- a model allowed to rewrite its own memory;
+- a guarantee that every source is complete;
+- a cloud service required to inspect one's own history;
+- an orchestrator that autonomously acts without operator-declared authority.
+
+## Product value
+
+For an individual, Sinex can support evidence-backed recall across tools rather than relying on memory or one application's history.
+
+For an agent, it can provide bounded, source-aware context and make omissions visible.
+
+For an operator, it can expose source health, replay, lifecycle, and model effects instead of hiding them behind generated prose.
+
+For research, it can provide longitudinal, cross-source evidence with explicit semantics and caveats.
+
+For Polylogue, it can become the durable material, event, lifecycle, and cross-domain backend while Polylogue remains the AI-work domain product.
+
+## Present state
+
+Sinex is pre-1.0 and optimized first for a demanding single-user deployment. The repository contains substantial capture, event-engine, replay, query, operations, MCP, schema, and deployment machinery. It has been exercised against a private archive with tens of millions of events.
+
+That deployment evidence establishes that a substantial system exists. It is not a general scalability benchmark. Broad recall latency, capture completeness, replay safety, derived-product usefulness, and public onboarding remain active Beads work.
+
+See [Proof and claims](proof-artifacts.md) for the claim taxonomy and [Public demonstrations](demos.md) for the proposed proof portfolio.
