+# Sinex proof artifacts and public claims
+
+Sinex should publish fewer claims and make each one easy to audit.
+
+## Claim classes
+
+| Claim class | Meaning | Required support |
+|---|---|---|
+| **Implemented capability** | A named operation exists in current code | Source location, public command/API, and contract test or bounded check |
+| **Deterministic proof** | A checked-in fixture satisfies a declared invariant | Input manifest, oracle, expected/observed result, exact commands, machine report |
+| **Private-deployment observation** | A result was measured on a named private archive/runtime | Date, corpus/host scope, method, caveats, and non-generalization statement |
+| **Experiment** | An intervention was compared with a baseline | Protocol, frozen inputs, scoring, uncertainty, negative controls, and limitations |
+| **Roadmap direction** | An owned future target | Bead ID, dependency state, acceptance criteria, and no shipped-language |
+| **Retired claim** | A prior design or issue no longer owns truth | Superseding code, Bead, or decision |
+
+Claim class is separate from evidence class. A deterministic proof may use a structural oracle; an experiment may use human adjudication; an implemented capability may lack a public construct-valid proof.
+
+## Evidence classes
+
+Preferred evidence, strongest first where applicable:
+
+1. externally authoritative state;
+2. provider/runtime-structured outcome;
+3. exact material bytes or record anchor;
+4. independently recomputed baseline;
+5. human adjudication under a written rubric;
+6. heuristic or model classification;
+7. unavailable or unsupported.
+
+A result should name its evidence class rather than letting polished prose imply strength.
+
+## Existing reproducible proof
+
+### Deterministic operational walkthrough
+
+Command:
+
+```bash
+sinexctl ops verify --demo
+```
+
+Generated documentation: [Sinex Demo Walkthrough](../crate/sinexctl/docs/demo_walkthrough.md).
+
+Declared scope: bounded deterministic operational smoke through normal surfaces. It is not a complete replay, coverage, durability, or cross-source thesis proof.
+
+### Existing tests and contracts
+
+The repository contains extensive unit, integration, schema, sandbox, source, event-engine, API, and CLI tests. Tests support specific implementation contracts; aggregate test count is not itself a product-value proof.
+
+Use `TESTING.md` and `xtask` for the current verification matrix.
+
+## Tracked field evidence
+
+### Production restore and recall campaign — `sinex-mhk`
+
+The closed Bead records a restored live deployment, event-count and source-material checks, a healthy serving runtime, and bounded recall against production data.
+
+The same record also preserves a serious caveat: recovery included an intentional stream purge to establish a new real-time boundary, and some material may have been recoverable. The campaign therefore proves a substantial live deployment and a repaired serving path; it does not prove lossless recovery under every failure.
+
+### Multi-source recall campaign — `sinex-9j9`
+
+The closed campaign required a side-by-side raw-source baseline, resolvable evidence, explicit source caveats, one-command regeneration, and a cold-reader check.
+
+Its construct is bounded recall over a real work window, not complete lifetime reconstruction.
+
+### Capture-coverage work — `sinex-jdp`
+
+The in-progress Bead promotes source gaps into a standing coverage-error measure. Its first private-deployment observation reported 58 of 64 evaluated source entries with at least one identified coverage error.
+
+That means 90.62% of source entries had some known coverage problem under the metric. It does **not** mean 90.62% of all real-world occurrences were lost.
+
+### Recall latency field note
+
+See [Recall Query Latency, 2026-07-03](../crate/sinex-db/docs/recall_query_latency_2026_07_03.md). This is a dated private-deployment diagnostic, not a general performance guarantee.
+
+## Public claim ledger
+
+The machine-readable source is [`public-claims.yaml`](public-claims.yaml). It should be validated in CI and used to render a human claims page.
+
+Each entry carries:
+
+- stable claim ID;
+- public wording;
+- claim class;
+- status;
+- evidence class;
+- scope;
+- evidence refs;
+- falsifier;
+- caveats;
+- owning Beads;
+- last review date.
+
+## Proof-packet contract
+
+A public demo or experiment should emit a packet with at least:
+
+```yaml
+packet_version: 2
+id: stable-demo-id
+software_revision: git-sha
+claim:
+  text: bounded public claim
+  class: deterministic-proof
+  scope: exact corpus and operation
+oracle:
+  kind: structural
+  expected: machine-checkable expectation
+  observed: machine-readable result
+falsifier: explicit failure condition
+controls:
+  - positive
+  - negative
+  - missing-evidence
+inputs:
+  manifest: inputs.json
+  digests: []
+evidence_refs: []
+caveats: []
+unsupported_claims: []
+commands: []
+artifacts:
+  report_json: report.json
+  report_markdown: report.md
+  transcript: transcript.txt
+```
+
+The verifier should fail when:
+
+- required artifacts are absent;
+- declared hashes do not match;
+- the expected oracle does not match the observed result;
+- evidence refs do not resolve;
+- a claim marked deterministic depends on undeclared live/private state;
+- unsupported claims are rendered as achieved.
+
+## Claims that should not appear unqualified
+
+Do not publish these without narrower scope and evidence:
+
+- “Sinex captures everything.”
+- “No data loss.”
+- “Replay is deterministic.”
+- “An empty result means nothing happened.”
+- “Semantic retrieval is better.”
+- “AI memory improves productivity.”
+- “Retroactive privacy deletes all traces.”
+- “Tens of millions of events proves general scalability.”
+- “Polylogue already runs on Sinex.”
+
+Use exact alternatives:
+
+- “The queried sources reported these coverage states.”
+- “This fault-injection proof preserved every acknowledged occurrence at this boundary.”
+- “Replay reinterprets preserved evidence under current semantics.”
+- “This private deployment held approximately N events on date D under the recorded configuration.”
+- “The Sinex-backed Polylogue architecture is planned under `sinex-4j2`; the current bridge is metadata-thin.”
